{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"13a5ff71-8320-49a8-85c0-e04e5c5f4583","content":".NET 8+ ships with `System.TimeProvider` — no custom abstraction needed.\n\n**In production code**, inject `TimeProvider`:\n\n```csharp\npublic class ReportGenerator\n{\n    private readonly TimeProvider _timeProvider;\n\n    public ReportGenerator(TimeProvider timeProvider)\n        => _timeProvider = timeProvider;\n\n    // Replace DateTime.UtcNow with:\n    var now = _timeProvider.GetUtcNow();\n}\n```\n\n**Register in DI:**\n\n```csharp\nservices.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);\n```\n\n**In tests**, use the built-in fake:\n\n```csharp\nvar fakeTime = new FakeTimeProvider(\n    new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 15, 9, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));\n\nvar generator = new ReportGenerator(fakeTime);\n\n// Advance time as needed:\nfakeTime.Advance(TimeSpan.FromHours(2));\n```\n\n> `FakeTimeProvider` lives in **`Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing`** — add it to your test project:\n> ```\n> dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing\n> ```\n\nThis gives you fully deterministic tests with zero custom code.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8990a680-531d-4ae4-b58c-e5c222ffdeae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to mock time in .NET 10 for unit testing. In .NET 8+, Microsoft introduced `TimeProvider` as a built-in abstraction for time. This is the recommended approach for .NET 10.\n\nLet me look at what's in the current working directory to understand the context better.","outputTokens":389,"requestId":"67C6:1E9A5D:18E372E:1C08BAF:69FD4510"},"id":"6635b017-6bd8-41ab-a416-8ddfdd21dde1","timestamp":"2026-05-08T02:06:17.965Z","parentId":"4574057d-cf06-475b-a4cd-cc76ee8dd9be"}
